Rating: 3
Following up on my resolution to eat more like a Mediterranean (see also Tunisian Soup with Chard, Chick Peas, and Egg Noodles), I jumped at the chance to try this unusual veggie/pasta/nut combination. As a bonus for those trying to be extra- virtuous in the kitchen, this recipe features an eco-friendly "snout to tail" approach to beets, using both the greens and the beets themselves. In my hands, there was no need to add a full cup of pasta cooking liquid -- a few splashes sufficed. My carnivore husband was slow to warm to this recipe, and so I had the leftovers for lunch the following day. These were greatly enhanced by the addition of crumbled aged goat cheese (Boucheron), which added creaminess and complemented the beets beautifully -- I will be sure to add these when I make the recipe again. I also modified the onion caramelization steps, using Mark Bittman's foolproof trick of placing thinly sliced onions directly in a dry med-high pan, with the lid on, for 5 minutes -- butter/oil is added after the onions have wilted and browned. I have come to believe that this is the quickest and most consistent way of caramelizing onions. Overall, a great, healthy recipe!

